=== Lesson 24-1 (Introduction) ===

 {"type":"h3","text":"Germaine's Guide to RC Main Conclusion Questions"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Main Idea questions ask you to identify the central idea of a passage..."}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"A good main point will answer the question: \"What is the one thing the author most wants me to understand after reading this?\"..."}
 {"type":"list","items":["A **problem** and the author's proposed **solution**.","A **common theory** and the author's **alteration** of it.","An **explanation** for a puzzling phenomenon.","A **comparison** of two or more things to arrive at a judgment."]}
+{{+**Note:** Some stems ask about the "primary purpose" rather than the "main point." These are closely related but distinct: main point = what the author argues; primary purpose = why the author wrote the passage. The approach is similar for both.+}}
 {"type":"hr"}
 {"type":"h3","text":"Stem Identification: How to Spot a Main Idea Question"}
-{"type":"paragraph","text":"Main Idea questions can be phrased in a few similar ways. They will usually ask you for a main point/idea/conclusion. Occasionally they will substitute \"central\" for \"main\" or directly ask for a \"summary.\""}
+{{~change~}} The stem identification intro paragraph restates the lesson opening. Trim to one sentence or cut entirely -- the breakdown below carries the definitional weight.
 {"type":"breakdown","labels":{"title":"Category","text":"Examples"},"items":[...]}
 {"type":"callout","title":"Overarching Takeaway","variant":"summary","text":"Don't get thrown off by the minor variations in wording..."}
 {"type":"h3","text":"The Importance of Main Conclusion Questions"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Main Idea questions appear about 225 times among the last 225 released LSATs, making up approximately 11%..."}
