=== Lesson 24-4 (Trap Answer Types) ===

 {"type":"h3","text":"Trap Answer Types"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Knowing what wrong answers look like is just as important as knowing the right one..."}
 {"type":"breakdown","labels":{"title":"Trap Type","text":"The Flaw"},"items":[
   {"title":"1. Inaccurate Information","text":"...Often, the first half is correct, but the second half slips in an error...","badge":"Factual Error","badgeColor":"red"},
   {"title":"2. Outside the Scope or Too Extreme","text":"...","badge":"Unsupported","badgeColor":"red"},
   {"title":"3. Too Narrow","text":"The most frequent distractor...","badge":"Partial Truth","badgeColor":"red"},
   {"title":"4. Opposing Viewpoint","text":"...","badge":"Wrong Side","badgeColor":"red"}
 ]}
+{{+**Missing:** Each trap type needs a concrete wrong-answer example. E.g., for "Too Narrow": "If a passage discusses both the causes and effects of deforestation, a too-narrow answer would only mention the causes."+}}
